arch:property.oc:show_val: 13107 Dry-sieved. This is a medium size unit. Cattle-size is slightly more frequent than sheep-size. There are no hare-size animals in the dry sieve (but there are in the flot). About 5% of all bones are burnt, although the degree of burning is variable. There is some partial burning, some low temperature (brown/black), and some medium-high temperature (carbonized) burning. Surface condition is, on the whole, fairly nice: half of the unit is in very good (condition: 2), and the other half is more trampled, beaten up, similar to midden material (condition: 3). In other words, some seem freshly buried, while others look as though they were worn a bit more before burial. There is a significant amount of medium to heavy carnivore gnawing, both on smaller and larger animal sizes (about 5%). The fragments in this unit are large, mostly between 5 and 12 cm, 8-9 cm average. This means that the fragments do not seem heavily processed. 70-80% of the unit consists of diagnostics. Taxa represented by the diagnostics are: equid, cattle, sheep/goat, and wild sheep. Diagnostics include, one red deer scapula fragment, one wild sheep horn core, one possibly wild sheep unfused distal tibia, one equid scapula fragment, one equid pelvis (acetabulum, and partial ilium and ischium), a distal radius fragment, an equid digit, several sheep/goat long bones and pelvis fragments, and a few cattle scapulae, long bones, atlas, axis and sacrum fragments, and two toes. Sheep/goat and/or sheep-size body-part distribution is uneven: Mostly long bones, pelvis fragments, and teeth and cranial bits to a smaller extent. Cattle and cattle-size body-part distribution is also uneven: Scapula fragments, some vertebrae, long bones and cranial fragments, a few teeth and two phalanges. The bones from all taxa come from meaty bones (mostly long bones, scapula and pelvis, though not many vertebral fragments). There aren’t many non-meaty parts, such as metapodial fragments, ankle/wrist bones or phalanges (the flotatio does not have them either, see flot FUD below). However, there are several cranial bones that are not as meaty as long bones, but meatier than feet bones. Surface conditions would indicate that a lot of the bones were freshly buried, but some of the bones with good surface condition also suggest having lain around due to the medium/heavy gnawing on them. Those pieces may be regular midden material, considering that Catalhoyuk bones from middens are usually in good surface condition (condition 2 to 3). Overall, this seems like a consumption deposit. The presence of meaty body parts coming from large animals, and the lack of heavy processing suggest feasting. However, the unit does not consist exclusively of these meaty body parts, so we can’t say that it all comes from one consumption event or feasting. It is probably the remains of one or more special consumption events (e.g. feasts) mixed in with some standard midden material. There is one bone tool made out of tibia distal end and shaft, and a plaster spatula fragment made out of a scapula fragment. Last number: 125. 13107, S2, Flotation# 6577, >4mm, 100%. Only diagnostics are recorded; the rest are treated as flot fragments (i.e. counted and weighed). This is a medium/large flotation sample. Most of the fragments (ca. 90%) in this unit are sheep-size, except a few microfauna pieces, a few hare/fox-size, a few pig-size, and a few cattle-size fragments. About 2-3% of the unit is burnt, mostly low temperature (burnt black). About 20% of the unit is in surface condition 2, and the rest is mostly 3. The overall surface condition is good considering the flotation sample typically looks more beaten-up than the dry-sieve. Only a couple long bone fragments have evidence for gnawing (light carnivore). However, a significant amount of small fragments (especially foot and ankle bones) are digested (5-10%). About half of the unit is freshly broken. The size of the fragments with old breaks varies between 1-8 cm, and but fragments with old breaks average to about 3 cm. About 20% of the unit consists of diagnostics: a considerable amount for a flot sample. Taxa represented by the diagnostics are equid, sheep, sheep/goat, cattle, pig, deer, medium canid (dog), and Vulpes sp.; a wide range of taxa. Diagnostics: equid metacarpal, deer antler fragment, canid pelvis (ilium), sheep cranial element and humerus, sheep/goat cranial elements, three wrist bones probably coming from the same wrist but not articulated, mandible with a teeth row (contains deciduous and permanent teeth), phalanges, knuckle bones, pig frontal fragment, and Vulpes sp. metacarpal fragment. Overall body-part distribution: Sheep-size and/or sheep/goat body part distribution: IDs are mostly teeth fragments, cranial pieces, and ankle and foot bones. All body parts, are, however present in at least small numbers. Ribs and long bones add up to a small amount. There are almost no vertebrae. Pig-size and/or pig body part distribution consists of a few long bone shaft fragment and one (pig) cranial piece. Cattle-size body part distribution consists of a few cranial pieces and long bone shaft fragments. The flot sample is similar to the dry-sieve sample in terms of surface condition and coherence. The flot has far less gnawing, but far more digestion than dry sieve. Unlike the dry-sieve, the flot sample is heavily sheep-size, but this may be due to recovery differences from the dry sieve. F198 is a bead from the flotation sample.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
